The erroneous code fails because the variable named variable lacks an initial value before the print statement executes. Java requires local variables to be initialized before use. The fix involves assigning a string value to variable prior to printing it.

Here is the corrected Main class:
```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The next class assigns a fresh value to the variable:
```java
public class AssignValue {
    public static void updateVariable(String input) {
        String variable = input;
        System.out.println("New value is " + variable);
    }
}
```

The following class performs string concatenation on the variable:
```java
public class ConcatenateString {
    public static void appendText(String input) {
        String variable = input;
        String result = variable + " and goodbye";
        System.out.println("Combined text is " + result);
    }
}
```

The final class compares the variable against another string:
```java
public class CompareString {
    public static boolean checkEquality(String input) {
        String variable = input;
        String target = "Hello world";
        return variable.equals(target);
    }
}
```
